## Discovery (IMPORTANT -- surfaced to user)
weave.publish(LLMStructuredCompletionModel(llm_model_id='gpt-4')) yields digest
R4haXWo7Y45rNOIu6OQQJOxTVYty395huswOAOkA9l4, NOT the corpus golden
eCEXZKYo6MdXGYfTnXgFef5PzBZg2YX1cVYMVozYcmc. These are DIFFERENT wire
representations of "the same" model:
- eCEXZKYo = server canonicalization of the RAW DICT {llm_model_id:'gpt-4'}
  tagged builtin_object_class=LLMStructuredCompletionModel (the frontend/wb_agent
  path; process_incoming_object_val -> dump_object(schema.model_validate(val))).
  Covered by the server test (obj_create with builtin_object_class) + library.
- R4haX = the Python SDK serializing the RUNNABLE Model object (weave/flow
  LLMStructuredCompletionModel(Model)), digest computed client-side.
Client and server AGREE on R4haX (publish succeeded -> server validated the
client's expected_digest), so there is NO client<->server drift. The corpus
(server canonicalization) simply does not pin the runnable's serialization.
OPEN QUESTION for the user: is it intended that publishing the model via the SDK
(runnable) produces a different ref/digest than the raw-dict+builtin-class path?
If both are meant to be "the same model", that is a cross-path dedup
inconsistency rooted in the PR2 runnable/schema split. Not investigated further
(would require diffing the runnable Model fields/bases vs the schema BaseObject).

